%	INTRODUCTION
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\mysec{Introduction}
\color{NavyBlue}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Due to reasons of confidentiality only \textbf{aggregated data} may be accessible. Area-level models in Small Area Estimation can contribute to improved domain predictions in terms of smaller variance in such situations.
  \item Starting from an unbiased but unreliable direct estimator we will show how outliers on the unit level will affect the area-level predictions. Two types of unit-level (\textbf{symmetric} and \textbf{representative}) contamination will be explored: \textbf{individual outliers} (single observations in a domain) and \textbf{area outliers} (all observations in a domain).
  \item We will show which type of contaminated data may call for a robustified estimation technique, and on the contrary in which case unit-level contamination is \textit{automatically} been taken care of in the Fay Herriot Model.
\end{itemize}



