%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%	CONCLUSIONS
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\mysec{Conclusions}
\color{NavyBlue}

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Individual outliers} lead to unreliable direct estimators. The FH and RFH estimators will \text{adjust} for that unreliablility. Both use the estimated standard error of the direct estimator to weight down unreliable direct estimators.
  \item The RFH will reduce the MSE of the domain predictions in the presence of \textbf{outlying areas} in contrast to the FH. However, a larger MSE is introduced for the outlying areas.
  \item In the \textbf{design-based simulation} the FH and RFH estimator improve the MSE but introduce a severe bias to the predictions. How that \textbf{bias} can be explained, while using an unbiased direct estimator is unclear at this time and needs further exploration.
  \item From a unit-level perspective, design weights can help to address heterogeneity in the data. However, outlier robustness can still be an issue, which may be solved in a second step in area-level models.
\end{itemize}

